[2] Dominican Republic
Date: Fri 9 Apr 2010
Source: People's Daily Online [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90782/90880/6945050.html>


At least 14 people have died of dengue fever this year [2010] in the
Dominican Republic, the health authorities said Wednesday [7 Apr
2010]. Health Minister Nelson Rodriguez said 2000 cases of dengue
fever have been registered, 291 of which were the hemorrhagic kind.
He said the country could have more dengue cases this year than last
year's [2009] 8800. A total of 52 died of the disease last year.

Rodriguez attributed the increase of the cases to the drought
affecting the country, which causes the appearance of the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito that harbors the virus.

Given the situation, the Health Ministry has expanded the prevention
plan and raised the epidemic alert.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts vis ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Minister of Health did not explain why the drought contributed
to the increase of _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, but it is likely due
to residents storing water in and around their houses, providing more
breeding sites for this vector mosquito.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Dominican Republic can
be accessed at <http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=18.9,-70.5,5>. -
