[7] Brazil (Minas Gerais)
Date: Tue 6 Apr 2010
Source: Globo.com [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]

There are now 3246 confirmed [dengue] cases in Carangola. The city
government says that it is taking the necessary steps [to deal with
the outbreak]. The Public [Justice] Ministry is charging the
Carangola city government for [failure to take] action to combat
dengue. Prosecutors said nearly 10 percent of the population already
had the disease. The case is in court.

In the municipality, there now have been 3246 confirmed cases.
"Despite efforts for public awareness, the population leaves many
foci [of mosquito breeding] and this favors proliferation of the
mosquito," said the Interim Secretary of Health, Anderson Barbosa.

In 2 months, Brazil has registered more than 220 000 dengue cases.
Rio Grande do Sul has registered more than 3400 dengue cases. Because
of the large number of cases, the Public [Justice] Ministry
Prosecutor filed a lawsuit and questions the actions of the
Municipality of Carambola. The Secretariat of Health is accused of
not meeting the standards of the National Program for Combat of
Dengue. "This program was not completed and was not observed, and
this led to the epidemic situation, " said prosecutor Mark Aguiar
Arle.

The Carangola Prefecture denied this accusation and stated that since
November of last year [2009], a vehicle that distributed poison
against the mosquito [abate larvicide?] went around the streets of
the city. Also, according to the municipal administration, 59 agents
work in combating dengue fever, and a task force of 15 men sent by
the State Health Department arrived on Monday [5 Apr 2010] to the
city to reinforce these actions.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is unfortunate that the situation has led to legal action. This
report does not indicate if prospective vector surveillance was being
carried out to determine if household vector mosquito infestation
indices were being reduced. Simply distributing insecticides without
an aggressive public education program coupled with technical
surveillance is not likely to be effective at reducing dengue virus
transmission. - Mod.TY]

******
[8] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Tue 6 Apr 2010
Source: Terra [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/noticias/0,,OI4366056-EI8139,00-Cresce+numero+de+casos+de+dengue+no+interior+baiano.html>


There has been an increase of 1500 percent in dengue cases in the
Bahia interior. The dengue epidemic is provoking alarm in the Bahia
[state] municipality of Jaguarari, at 400 km [249 miles] from
Salvador. With just 13 000 inhabitants, the municipality has
registered 229 suspected dengue cases, with 20 laboratory confirmed,
since the beginning of the year [2010]. In the 1st 3 months of last
year [2009], there were 16 reported cases with 7 confirmed.

The increase in the number of suspected dengue cases and infestations
of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito led to coordination of municipal
epidemiology to intensify combat of foci of mosquito breeding sites.
Meetings and pamphlet distributions were carried out with help from
schools, shopkeepers and society. "We intensified action; the
collaboration began at the beginning of February [2010] and was
completed in March 2010. We went along the streets carrying out
house-to-house work to make people aware of how to proceed in the
house to avoid foci for the disease," said Ana Patricia Lima de
Oliveira, nurse of the Familia de Pilar Health Post. According to
her, one of the main causes in the increase of [mosquito] infections
is the accumulation of trash in open areas, vacant lots and storm
drains.

In the entire state there have been 5 deaths.

--
