[10] Indonesia (Bali)
Date: Mon 5 Apr 2010
Source: The Jakarta Post [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2010/04/05/two-die-dengue-fever.html>


The yearly dengue fever outbreak claimed the lives of 2 children at
Sanglah Hospital last week. The 2 victims were a 4-year-old from
Badung regency who died Thursday [1 Apr 2010], and an 11-year-old
from Karangasem regency who died Friday [2 Apr 2010]. Both patients
had only been treated for a day.

At least 6 people -- 4 of them children -- have died of the disease
at the hospital this year [2010]," Ken Wirasandhi, head of the
hospital's service department, said. "Both victims suffered from
dengue shock syndrome."

Dengue patients experience shock from symptoms developed following
the incubation period of between 3-10 days. Dengue shock syndrome is
indicated by rising blood pressure, which is caused by the dengue
virus attacking red blood cells.

Ken said that the hospital's environment also posed a risk of
spreading dengue fever to relatives of dengue patients staying at the
hospital. Therefore, he said, the hospital management would put in
place strict measures to exterminate mosquitoes. "We will use
electric mosquito repellents in all rooms and fumigate every week,"
he said. "We also counsel patients' relatives every Tuesday and
Thursday."

Many patients are still unaware of the need to immediately get tests
done if they experience persistent fevers, Ken said, adding that
these people wrongly believe they have only contracted a common fever
or influenza, he added.

Initial dengue symptoms include a fever that persists for between 3-7
days followed by pain in the bones and red spots on the skin.

--
